<section xml:id="sec-ctsbyhand">
  <title>Showing Continuity by Hand</title>
  
<p>
  Last time, we proved using the definition that a linear function is continuous at a point, and we showed it is continuous on all of <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
</p>
<p>
  We also proved using the definition that the squaring function <m>y=x^2</m> is continuous at a point, and we showed it is continuous on all of <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
</p>
<p>
  We could do the same for the square root function <m>y=\sqrt{y}</m>, showing that it is continuous on its domain of all reals <m>x \geq 0</m>.  A similar proof will show that <m>y=\sqrt[n]{y}</m> is continuous for natural numbers <m>n \geq 2</m>.
</p>
<p>
  Using the definition to show that the cosine function is continuous at <m>x=c</m> uses the following facts:
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>\cos(x)-\cos(c) = -2 \sin\left( \frac{x+c}{2} \right) \sin \left( \frac{x-c}{2} \right)</m>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>| \sin \theta | \leq 1</m>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>| \sin \theta | \leq |\theta|</m>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Because <m>x=c</m> is arbitrary, the proof can show that the cosine function is continuous on all reals.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</p>

</section>

<section xml:id="sec-ctsfcns">
  <title>Continuous Functions</title>
  
  <p>
  Last time we proved that a linear function is continuous on all of <m>\mathbb{R}</m>, and we proved that the squaring function is, too.  The proofs revealed something about how the choice of <m>\delta</m> depends (or doesn't) on both <m>\epsilon</m> and the points at which we're establishing continuity, i.e., <m>x=c</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    We will see that, as a consequence of the Algebraic Continuity Theorem, polynomials are continuous functions on all of <m>\mathbb{R}</m> 
  </p>
  <p>
    The same theorem will tell us that rational functions (which are quotients of polynomials) are continuous on their domain (which is all of <m>\mathbb{R}</m> minus the finite number of points at which their denominator vanishes).
  </p>
  <p>
    We'd like to know that other elementary functions are continuous on their domains, too.  These include
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          algebraic functions
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          trigonometric functions
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          exponential functions
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          logarithm functions
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
<p>
  Other special functions, such as the hyperbolic trigonometric functions, are algebraic combinations of the above.  Others, like the Normal (a.k.a., Gaussian) probability distribution function, is a functional composition of the above.
</p>
<p>
  We won't go through the details for exponential functions, for example, but we can show from first principles that the exponential functions are continuous on their domain.
</p>
<p>
  We have other theorems that will help us prove the other functions are continuous without relying on the definition.
</p>
</section>

<section xml:id="sec-algctsthm">
  <title>Algebraic Continuity Theorem</title>

<p>
  
</p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-algcts">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Assume <m>f : A → \mathbb{R}</m> and <m>g : A → \mathbb{R}</m> are continuous at a point <m>c \in A</m>. Then,
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>kf(x)</m> is continuous at <m>c</m> for all <m>k \in \mathbb{R}</m>;
    </p>
  </li>
  <li xml:id="item-thm-algcts2">
    <p>
      <m>f(x)+g(x)</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>;
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>f(x)g(x)</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>; and
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>f(x)/g(x)</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>, provided the quotient is defined.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
</p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>

  <proof>
    <p>
      Let's prove (<xref ref="item-thm-algcts2"/>).
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>(x_n) \subset A</m> be a sequence that converges to <m>c</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Then because <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m> are continuous at <m>c</m>, the sequences <m>(f(x_n))</m> and <m>(g(x_n))</m> converge to <m>f(c)</m> and <m>g(c)</m>, respectively.
      </p>
    <p>
      By the Algebraic Limit Theorem for sequences, we know <m>(f(x_n)+g(x_n))</m> converges to <m>f(c)+g(c)=(f+g)(c)</m>.  Therefore, by the sequential characterization of functional limits, we can conclude that <m>(f(x)+g(x))</m> converges to <m>f(c)+g(c)=(f+g)(c)</m> as <m>x \rightarrow c</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The other items in the theorem statement are provides analogously.
    </p>
  </proof>

  <p>
    With this (and some of our previous by-hand proofs) we can, with induction, show all polynomials are continuous on their domain.  And all rational functions.  And all trigonometric functions.  And all algebraic functions.
  </p>
  <p>
    Lots of functions.
  </p>
</section>

<section xml:id="sec-compctsfcn">
  <title>Composition of Continuous Functions</title>
    
  <p>
    This next theorem increases the variety of functions that we can say are continuous, such as these:
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\sqrt{x^2+x+1}</m>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\cos(x^2)</m>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>e^{-x^2}</m>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>
  <theorem xml:id="thm-compctsfcn">
    <title>Composition of Continuous Functions</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Given <m>f : A \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> and <m>g : B \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m>, assume that the range <m>f(A) = \{f(x) : x \in A\}</m> is contained in the domain <m>B</m> so that the composition <m>g \circ f(x) = g(f(x))</m> is defined on <m>A</m>.  If <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>c \in A</m>, and if <m>g</m> is continuous at <m>f(c) \in B</m>, then <m>g \circ f</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  
  <proof>
    <p>
      Easy proof if you use the sequential characterization of continuity at a point.
    </p>
  </proof>
</section>

<p workspace="4in"></p>

<section xml:id="sec-ctscpt">
  <title>Continuous functions and Compact Sets</title>
  
<theorem xml:id="thm-ctscpt">
  <title>Preservation of Compact Sets</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>f : A \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> be continuous on <m>A</m>. If <m>K \subseteq A</m> is compact, then <m>f(K)</m> is compact as well.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Suppose that <m>K \subseteq A</m> is compact.  We want to show that
      <md>
        <mrow>f(K) = \{f(y) \, : \, y \in K \}</mrow>
      </md>
      is compact.  We will show that <m>f(K)</m> is sequentially compact.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>(y_n)</m> be a sequence in <m>f(K)</m>.  We must show that it has a subsequence that converges to a limit in <m>f(K)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Fix <m>k \in \mathbb{N}</m>.  Since <m>y_k \in f(K)</m> there is an <m>x \in K</m> with the property that <m>f(x)=y_k</m>.  Call this element of <m>x=x_k</m>.  We can find such an element for each <m>k \in \mathbb{N}</m>.  This gives us a sequence <m>(x_n) \subset K</m>.  Now we can use information about <m>K</m> begin compact.
    </p>
    <p>
      Since <m>K</m> is compact, <m>(x_n)</m> has a convergent subsequence <m>(x_{n_k})</m>.  Let <m>x_0</m> be the limit of this subsequence.  Since <m>K</m> is compact, <m>x_0 \in K</m>.  Therefore, <m>f(x_0) \in f(K)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      At the same time, <m>(f(x_{n_k}))</m> is a subsequence of <m>(y_n) \subset f(K)</m>. Moreover, because <m>f</m> is continuous on <m>K</m>, the sequence <m>f(x_{n_k}) \subset f(K)</m> converges to <m>f(x_0)</m>.  Thus, our subsequence converges in <m>f(K)</m>.  Therefore, <m>f(K)</m> is compact, as desired.
    </p>
  </proof>
</theorem>

</section>


<section xml:id="sec-evt">
  <title>Extreme Value Theorem</title>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-extrememvalue">
    <title>Extreme Value Theorem</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>f : K \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> is continuous on a compact set <m>K \subset \mathbb{R}</m>, then <m>f</m> attains a maximum and minimum value. In other words, there exist <m>x_0, x_1 \in K</m> such that <m>f(x_0) \leq f(x) \leq f(x_1)</m> for all <m>x \in K</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  
<proof>
  <p>
    Suppose <m>f</m> is continuous on a compact set <m>K \subset \mathbb{R}</m>.  By <xref ref="thm-ctscpt"/>, <m>f(K)</m> is compact.  Therefore, because <m>f(K)</m> is closed and bounded, it contains the two limit points <m>\alpha = \sup(f(K))</m> and <m>\beta=\inf(f(K))</m>.  Since <m>\alpha \in f(K)</m>, there is an <m>x_0 \in K</m> for which <m>f(x_0)=\inf f(K)</m>.  Since <m>\beta \in f(K)</m>, there is an <m>x_1 \in K</m> for which <m>f(x_1)=\sup f(K)</m>.  Therefore, 
    <md>
      <mrow><m>f(x_0) =\inf f(K) \amp \leq f(x) \leq \sup f(K) = f(x_1)</m> </mrow>
    </md>
    <p>
      This shows that <m>f</m> attains both it absolute maximum and absolute minimum on <m>K</m>, as claimed.
    </p>
  </p>
</proof>

<p workspace="4in"></p>


</section>


<section xml:id="sec-unifcts">
  <title>Uniform Continuity</title>
  
<p>
  Our definition of continuity (see <xref ref="def-cts"/>) expresses the idea that as <m>x</m> gets closer and closer to <m>c</m>, the value of <m>f(x)</m> gets closer and closer to the value <m>f(c)</m>.  This means that we can make <m>|f(x)-f(c)|</m> as small as we want by making <m>|x-c|</m> small enough.  
</p>
<p>
  We've seen through examples that how small we make <m>|x-c|</m> can depend both on <m>\epsilon</m> and <m>c</m>.
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        In our proof of continuity of <m>f(x)=7x+5</m> we saw that <m>\delta=\epsilon/7</m> works.  Notice:  no dependence on <m>c</m>!
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        In a proof of continuity of <m>f(x)=\sqrt{x}</m> at a nonzero <m>x=c</m> we would see that <m>\delta=\epsilon \cdot \sqrt{c}</m> works.  Here, if <m>|c|</m> is small, then it it forces <m>\delta</m> to be smaller! 
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        In our proof of continuity of <m>f(x)=x^2</m> we saw that <m>\delta=\epsilon/(2|c|+1))</m> works.  Here, if <m>|c|</m> is big, then it forces <m>\delta</m> to be smaller.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</p>

<p>
  For some functions, the point at which we are working (i.e., <m>x=c</m>) plays an important role (viz a viz <m>f(x)=x^2</m>).
</p>
<p>
  For other functions (e.g., <m>f(x)=\sqrt{x}</m> and <m>f(x)=7x+5</m>), where we are examining continuity plays less of a role.
</p>

<p workspace="4in"></p>


<definition xml:id="def-unifcts">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A function <m>f : A \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> is uniformly continuous on <m>A</m> if for every <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m> there exists a <m>\delta &gt; 0</m> such that for all <m>x,y \in A</m> with <m>|x-y| &lt; \delta</m> we know <m>|f(x)-f(y)| &lt; \epsilon</m>
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>
</section>

<section xml:id="sec-unifcts2">
  <title>Uniformly Continuous Functions</title>
  
<theorem xml:id="thm-unifcts">
  <title>Uniform Continuity on Compact Sets</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A function that is continuous on a compact set <m>K</m> is uniformly continuous on <m>K</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <proof>
    <p>
      Let <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m> be given.  Since <m>f</m> is continuous on <m>K</m>, for each <m>c \in K</m> there is a <m>\delta = \delta(c) &gt; 0</m> for which <m>x \in V_{\delta(c)}(c)</m> implies <m>f(x) \in V_{\frac{1}{2}\epsilon}(f(c))</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Note that <m>V_{\frac{1}{2} \delta(c)}(c)</m> is the set of all <m>x \in K</m> for which <m>|x-c| &lt; \frac{1}{2}\delta(c)</m>.  The collection
      <md>
        <mrow>\mathcal{U}  \amp = \{ V_{\frac{1}{2} \delta(c)}(c) \, : \, c \in K \}</mrow>
      </md>
      is an open cover of <m>K</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Since <m>K</m> is compact, <m>\mathcal{U}</m> contains a finite subcover <m>\mathcal{U}_0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      This means that there are a finite number of points <m>c_i \in K</m>, where <m>i=1,2,3,\dots,n</m>such that
      <md>
        <mrow>K \subset V_{\frac{1}{2} \delta(c_1)}(c_1) \cup  V_{\frac{1}{2} \delta(c_2)}(c_2) \cup \cdots \cup V_{\frac{1}{2} \delta(c_n)}(c_n) \cup </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      Define <m>\delta = \frac{1}{2} \min \{ \delta(c_i) \, : \, i=1,2,3,\ldots,n\}</m>.  Then <m>\delta &gt; 0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>x,y \in K</m> such that <m>|x-y| &lt; \delta</m>.  Since <m>\mathcal{U}_0</m> is an open cover, there is a <m>1 \leq m \leq n</m> for which <m>x \in V_{\frac{1}{2} \delta(c_m)}(c_m)</m>.  That means <m>|x-c_m| &lt; \frac{1}{2} \delta(c_m)</m>.  We also have
      <md>
        <mrow>|y-c_m| \amp = |y-x+x-c_m|  </mrow>
        <mrow>\amp \leq |y-x|+|x-c_m|  </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp &lt; \delta  + \frac{1}{2} \delta(c_m)</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp &lt; \delta(c_m)</mrow>
      </md>
      It follows that
      <md>
        <mrow>|f(x)-f(y)| \amp = |f(x)-f(c_m)+f(c_m)-f(y)|</mrow>
        <mrow>|\amp \leq |f(x)-f(c_m)|+|f(c_m)-f(y)|</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp &lt; \epsilon/2 | \epsilon/2 </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = \epsilon</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      This shows that <m>f</m> is uniformly continuous on <m>K</m>.
    </p>
  </proof>
</theorem>

  
  
</section>
